segments.text: A black delegate was going to be coming from to the campus and how would the campus react and how could we prepare for this and so of course all of us on the executive committee were in favor of it.
We did not want to publicize it however because

We didn't want to give any, if there were any rednecks, we didn't want to give lead time for any opposition to form and to create problems or demonstrations or anything that might bring bad attention to A&M.
So we decided we wouldn't publicize it.
Nobody would say anything other than to make arrangements behind the scenes.
And I think they had made arrangements for him to stay with, I think Wayne or somebody that Wayne knew had made arrangements for him to stay with maybe the black minister in the community.
And then later decided to put him in at the MSC.
And it all worked out okay.
And it all worked out okay.
Well, it did except that on the first day,
When all the delegates began to arrive and they realized there was a black delegate there, some of the delegates who were our guests wanted to make a real big deal of it.
They wanted to focus on him as if he were a celebrity rather than focus on the topic of SCONA.
And we said, no, we don't want to do that.
Everything's going to be normal.
You're not going to make him a cause celebre.
focus on this.
And we had to do almost some arm twisting and almost threatened to send some of them home as being ungracious guests if they didn't settle down.
And I remember having to talk to some of the delegates that wanted to do that, to publicize this, and telling them, look, we want to set a precedent.
We want it to go well.
We don't want to give an opposition chance to form.
We wanted to do it, treat everything as if it's normal, and we'll publicize it after the fact.
You can still get all the mileage that you want out of it, but without creating a big incident.
And finally, we convinced them, the cooler heads prevail, to not make this a big thing, and it went well.
It was a precedent-setting move.
What about one or two of the highlights, the high points?
That one ended up positively, but some other things that you remember being very proud of in your Scona leadership years?
We initiated what we called at the time cultural leadership activities.
Wayne and one of his assistants named Bill Height and I went down to Houston.
We met with John Lindsay, we met with Nina Vance at the Alley Theater, we met with a number of folks, the director of the Houston Symphony Orchestra, I don't remember that name right now, but

What we wanted to do was to have a cultural weekend with selected student leaders on campus being invited to go by invitation, not by volunteer group, because we knew it had to be, especially initially, had to be a small control group.
And we did that in Houston, and that one went well.
So the next year, we did one in Dallas, including the, we timed it for the opera, Dallas opera season.

and uh and that kicked off it took hold and it's been going ever since and it's now called spring leadership it has it has evolved some in selection criteria and what they do and where they go but basically that was initiated in 60 61 or 62. the second one was the msc travel committee
And this was one of Wayne's brainstorms.
He probably got the idea from some of his association conferences with other student union leaders, but the idea was to

publicize and attract and motivate students to want to go any kind of an overseas experience so we got a lot of literature on things like the experiment international living uh... this operation crossroads
and any other kinds of activities that would facilitate and just publicize opportunities.
And then the students, of course, would have to volunteer and sometimes raise money and pay for them themselves.
But it was a great experience.
Well, that first year, I got caught up with the publicity and what we're doing.
That's when I signed up for that Operation Crossroads to East Africa.
Reggie Richardson, who was the deputy corps commander, was the first chairman of the Travel Committee and he got all the information, all the publicity together and helped facilitate this.
We had four people, two of us went on Operation Crossroads and two to experiment international living.
And then the next year, there were several more.
And then my brother, who came in as a freshman the year I graduated, we overlapped there in the fall of 63.
But he eventually became active in the MSC.
And I think he was a travel committee chairman.
And he went to Switzerland with the experiment in international living.
as a result of that.
So he was also in Hellcat 9.
Do you realize now in looking back that your MSC activities were important to your development?
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.
That was, I think it was all, it all contributed.
But I would say

Those three years as the Great Issues Committee Chairman and as Vice President and as President of the MSC Council and Directorate, probably if I had to give the key, the top among a lot of different influences and developmental high points, that would have to rate at the top.
Let's see, I'm looking at lesser matters here.
Describe going to an Aggie basketball game in those years.
I went to several of them.
I had played basketball in high school, but we were in G. Raleigh White.
And it was crowded.
It was, no, not very crowded.
No, there was plenty of space available for basketball games even then.
I think you said that tongue in cheek, didn't you?
I don't think I ever went to a basketball game in G. Raleigh-White where it was a packed house.
Because I don't think during my four years there,
I don't think we ever even got into Southwest Conference playoffs.
And so, although, I'm trying to think who the coach was.
Was it Shelby Metcalf there that early?
Shelby was an assistant coach then, Bob Rogers.
Bob Rogers, okay, I remember that name.
And the change would have come at about your senior year, somewhere about that time.
63 or 64, maybe, yeah, okay.
But that was...

you know that the team was good and I knew some of the guys I knew you know Jerry Windham and Lee Walker and Jim Keller were some of the guys on the team that uh... but I didn't know any of them really well oh Louis Qualls the guy was I knew him because

he was from Smiley and when I was in high school I played against him and when Conroe played Smiley I was assigned to guard Lewis Qualls and here I was about at that time about five ten or five eleven and he's like six ten or six eleven and after the game you know the folks were in high school were you know kind of consoling me about
how well, how hard I tried and how well I'd tried.

I'd fouled out early in the fourth quarter because I was trying too aggressively to keep him from getting the ball and try to guard him and they were trying to console me and so I told him, I said, I told Lewis once when we were standing side by side on the free throw line at one time, I told him, I said, if he didn't behave and quit pushing me around, I was going to punch him right in the knee.
But he was a tall drink of water.
What other student organizations had a high profile during that time other than the Corps and the MSC?
What about singing cadets?
Singing cadets were very popular.
They were still fairly early in their growth cycle.
You may happen to know what year
Bob Boone started.
I don't know if it was 59 or 60 or 61.
It was fairly early.
He was new and he was building and I don't know who his predecessor was or if he had a predecessor but it was building but it was still very impressive
then we always enjoyed hearing them sing.
What about Yale leaders?
How much prestige did Yale leaders have?
They had a lot.

Probably, they were probably, because they were more visible, they probably had more prestige and influence than student body presidents or MSC council presidents or I think that because they were so visible at football games, they probably, I think they and the corps commanders

in fact they probably even had more more visibility and prestige even than the corps commander did as far as uh because you know at the yell leader at the yell practices over in the grove and at the games themselves the head yell leader and the yell leaders were up you know that they were up rallying the troops and telling the fables and leading the yells and everything so with the the other folks you're more behind the scenes and don't have the
the visibility or the publicity that the Yale leaders did.
Did you know that secret fraternities existed?
I did not.
I have heard in subsequent years that some did.
I was never invited to join one and actually was kind of revolted at the idea of secret fraternities because to me that smacks of elitism.
For sure, maybe it's a way of networking and a way of maneuvering yourself and your buddies into positions of power and influence, but I don't like that.
I prefer a meritocracy where people can, by their talent and their hustle and their leadership, I just think it's easier to sustain that, whereas if a secret cabal is holding you in place,

and you're dependent more on them than you are on the facts and genuinely polling and leading public opinion to help you, you can maneuver yourself into some pretty untenable positions and then you either have to

have your cabal artificially hold you in place or else you kind of go down in flames and disgrace with nobody supporting you publicly because if your cabal comes out to support you then they identify themselves and I just don't like that system and yet I kind of suspect some of that might still be going on.
You did know about steam tunnels.
Yep.
Did you ever go down in the steam?
Absolutely.
When we were, again, my freshman year, when we were over in dorm seven, from the back of the dorm, you could see the band hall.
And the band had abused us on one occasion.
We had done very well that semester with some of the, well, the previous week had done well at a march off and had won it.
and had beaten either one of their units or one of their favorites.

And maybe there might have been some personal rivalries between some of our upperclassmen and some of them, but at any rate, during a march-off, there's a way you can do an offbeat roll-off between songs.
The drummers will roll, and if they intend to do this,
They'll roll and then start the next song one beat early which means that you're on the wrong foot as you come by.
And they did that to us as we were approaching the reviewing stand.

and as a result we had some guys you know we'd been told if that happens you just continue you don't do a change step you just continue and you shift to the right foot well some of the few of the guys didn't remember that or were confused and they were used to hitting the beat on the left foot so they changed step others didn't and so here we are
out of sync as we go by the reviewing stand.
So we get a bad grade that week.
Well, we seethe and simmer about that a little bit and we decide we're going to flood the band dorm.
And so we did some intelligence collection.
We got in the steam tunnels.
Earl Henderson and I again were, in fact Earl drew up the

the ops plan the sequencing of events and the timing and everything and we did the recon ordering in there knowing where found in the steam tunnels most of the the valves the wheels on the valves had been removed so you just had the stem coming out with the little square thing on it but it was to prevent the tampering with it but we had found one and had stored it in our room
And so we had a way to turn the main valve.
So we knew then, once we had found that, we knew we could do it if the guys didn't get caught.
So one day at noon, we had some fish dressed up as sophomores, and they were wearing their hats and wearing the slick black belt and the black braid so they could go in and disguise themselves.
And in case anybody was left in the dorm, well, sure enough, there was a guy in the dorm and he didn't go to chow with them.

and they said well we're up here we're looking for Fish Rabel or uh... uh... or uh... we're looking for Chip Rabel who was a sophomore this was a fish but it was from the same hometown from Spring Branch knew a name to drop and he said he said well you won't find him uh... he said he's at Chow and besides well he wouldn't why would you expect him to be here during Chow he said well we were supposed to meet him and uh... we're running late we thought he might have waited for us and so anyway the guy went on back into his room
and then later on got a little bit suspicious, but by this time, that group retreated.
We had a group going to every floor, every bathroom, taking the heads off of the flush toilets after the water was turned off.

and they got those well that group didn't do theirs but the other see two four six we got seven out of eight of the bathrooms done I was in the steam tunnel with the wheel and as the last guy left on his way out of the building he gave the secret knock on the door and turned the valve and then beat feet

back through and get to our dorm and then we're in that window looking out that back window to see what the reaction was and just as those guys were leaving the guy who had been contacted had second thoughts and he thought

something's happening and he went out and as he was going out the door he was headed out the door to sound a warning when the flood started and so they they reacted pretty quickly because he ran right across there to the chow hall and then all the band people ran back so there was a good indo-chinese fire drill there i need to quit because i got to be at him okay
